Why this matters
---------------------

  Everything in Kubernetes — kubectl, the scheduler, controllers, 
  CRDs, your own Go programs — is ultimately just talking to the 
  API server over HTTP/REST (with protobuf or JSON). 

  Understanding its structure, versioning, discovery, and watch-
  semantics makes everything else click. 

  It also explains why certain operations are fast or slow, how 
  CRDs extend the system cleanly, and why informers exist.



Key Concepts to Internalize
------------------------------
  * API Groups & Versions: 
      core (v1), apps/v1, networking.k8s.io/v1, apiextensions.k8s.io/v1, etc. 
      Newer groups live under /apis/....

  * Resources vs Kinds: 
      pods is the resource name; Pod is the Kind. 
      Plural vs singular matters in the API.

  * REST API structure: 
      /api/v1/namespaces/{ns}/pods, 
      /apis/apps/v1/namespaces/{ns}/deployments, etc.

  * Discovery: 
      How kubectl and clients figure out what the 
      server supports (/apis, /api/v1, OpenAPI schema).

  * Watch semantics: 
      Long-lived connections that stream changes (the 
      foundation of informers and efficient controllers). 
      Not polling.

  * API Server responsibilities: 
      Authentication, authorization (RBAC), admission 
      (validating/mutating webhooks), validation, 
      storage in etcd, and serving.


